The transition function \delta _{\mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}}\colon  \mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (Q_{M}\right )\mathclose {}} \times \Sigma \to \mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (Q_{M}\right )\mathclose {}} is so that a set of states S transitions along the symbol a\in  \Sigma  to the set of states reachable via a from some element of S:

   \delta _{\mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}}{\mathopen {}\left (S,a\right )\mathclose {}} =
   {\mathopen {}\left \{
    q'\in Q_{M}
   \,\middle \vert \,
    \exists  q\in  S\mathpunct {.}
    q\mathrel {\xRightarrow {a}} q' \text { in } M
   \right \}\mathclose {}}


  (Optional observation: this is a relational direct image.)

An accepting set of states is one that contains an accepting state from M:

   F_{\mathcal {P}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}} =
   {\mathopen {}\left \{S\subseteq Q_{M}\,\middle \vert \,
    \exists  q\in  S\mathpunct {.}
    q\in F_{M}
   \right \}\mathclose {}}

